# Playwright Architecture
1️⃣ What is Playwright Architecture?
Playwright Architecture explains how Playwright interacts with browsers to automate web applications.
It describes:
    1. How test scripts communicate with browsers
    2. How commands are executed
    3. How playwright manages multiple browsers and sessions

Playwright follows a Client-Server Architecture Model.

2️⃣ Main Components of Playwright Architecture
Playwright architecture mainly contains three core components.
Test Script (Client)
        │
        │ WebSocket / Protocol
        ▼
Playwright Server
        │
        │ Browser Protocol (CDP / Custom)
        ▼
Browser Engines

3️⃣ Client (Test Script)
The client is the code written by user
Example Languages supported:
    1. Python
    2. Javascript
    3. Typescript
    4. Java
    5. .NET

Example:
    page.goto("httsp://example.com")
    page.click("text=login")

The client sends commands to playwright.
Example commands:
    1. Open browser
    2. Navigate to URL
    3. Click element
    4. fill input

4️⃣ Playwright Server

The playwright server acts as bridge between the test script and browser.
Responsiblities:
    1. Receives commands from the test script
        -> When the test script executes an action like click() , fill() , goto() , etc.. the command is sent t
            the playwright server
    2. Converts commands into browser-level instructions
        -> The server converts the automation command into instructions that the browser understands
    3. Executes the action in the browser
        -> The browser performs the requested operation (for example clicking a button or navigating to a page)
    4. Returns results back to the test script
        -> After execution , the result (success or error) is sent back to the test script 
    Flow Diagram
    ------------
        Test Script
            │
            │  (click command)
            ▼
        Playwright Server
            │
            │ (convert to browser instructions)
            ▼
        Browser
            │
            │ (execute action)
            ▼
        Playwright Server
            │
            ▼
        Test Script (result)
Example flow:
    click button
        ↓
    Playwright server converts command
        ↓
    Browser receives instruction

5️⃣ Browser Engines
Playwright controls real browser engines.
Supported engines:
    Browser Engine & Example Browser
    --------------------------------
    1. Chromium -> Chrome , Edge
    2. FireFox -> Mozilla FireFox
    3. WebKit -> Safari

Playwright communicates with browsers using browser debugging protocols.
Example:
    1. Chromium -> Chrome DevTools Protocol (CDP)
    2. FireFox -> custom protocol
    3. WebKit -> custom protocol

6️⃣ Communication Protocol
Playwright uses a WebSocket connection between client and server.
Why WebSocket?
    Advantages:
        1. Fast communication
        2. Real-time interaction
        3. Single persistent connection
This makes playwright faster and more stable than traditional HTTP-based automation tools.

7️⃣ Browser Context (Important Concept)
Playwright uses Browser Contexts.
A browser context is an isolated browser session.
Example:
    Browser
   │
   ├── Context 1 (User A)
   │      └── Page
   │
   ├── Context 2 (User B)
   │      └── Page

Features:
    1. Separate cookies
    2. Separate local storage
    3. Multiple users in same browser

This helps:
    1. Parallel testing
    2. session isolation

8️⃣ Page and Frame Structure
Inside a browser context:
    Browser
   │
   └── Context
          │
          └── Page (Tab)
                 │
                 └── Frame (iframe)

Explanation
-----------
    Component & Meaning
    -------------------
    1. Browser -> Browser instance
    2. Context -> Isolated session
    3. Page -> Browser tab
    4. Frame -> iframe inside page

9️⃣ Execution Flow
When test runs , the flow is:
    1. Test script executes
    2. Playwright launches browser
    3. Commands sent to server
    4. Server sends instructions to browser
    5. Browser performs actions
    6. Results returned to test scripts.
Example:
    Test Code
        ↓
        Playwright
        ↓
        Browser
        ↓
        Web Application

🔟 Why Playwright Architecture is Powerful
Advatanges:
    1. Fast execution
    2. Direct browser control
    3. Parallel execution
    4. Cross-browser support
    5. Isolated browser contexts
This architecture reduces flaky tests and improves reliability.

